commentBody:
@Barry Ancona

Agreed. A nice Friday puzzle.

It looks like this is the "new normal", in which the editors will throw us a chewy Saturday once a month, as a "bone" to the base.

@Al  in Pittsburgh LEHANE is a new name to me. I don't read many new novels, don't check the NYT for reading suggestions, and don't pay attention to who wrote the book the movie was based on.
But heck, puzzle solving requires a lot of trivial knowledge, which is why I never solve late week puzzles without help from these forums.
I've forgotten 80% of everything I've learned.

@Al  in Pittsburgh

Yes, absolutely. Just because an author has been producing for twenty years, he isn’t necessarily famous. I don’t read current fiction, but I do know lots of famous recent authors—Clancy, Grisham, Rowling, Morrison, etc. 

I don’t think LAHANE is famous the way those are, and I don’t thin the A is as inferable as the A in, say, Clancy would be.

@Steve L

I didn't know the name, and I was looking at it while trying to fix EMAILScAM.  I did know Mystic River was about Irish-American people, so I thought LEHANE was more likely.  

But the possibility of ETALII did get me thinking as to whether it could be Dennis LEviNE.  (OSCARHOSTS was pretty set as a cross though)

@DJ

I didn't get the purpose of the busyness in the Mini.  You get a bonus arch that spells out the name of a famous bridge, and half-colored-in squares that represent what, lanes of traffic and water?  But I didn't see anything else in the puzzle that related.  Also, "Giants" should not be in the clue for NYG.

This puzzle left me shrugging my shoulders.

@Barry Ancona
The die is CAST....
I guess I can sort of see it, but PAST was the only thought I had...  and filters catch SPAM, but I doubt they spot SCAMs.

@Barry Ancona or perhaps in the sense of “cast off” or “cast away”? 

Also not sure I’ve ever heard of a “scam” filter, although some filters are now more adept at catching EMAIL SPAM that is also a scam than they used to be. 

So, I guess I can see it, but still seems like a stretch to me.

@Ryan 

Raising a nit-picking objection, then having someone call it out because the clue was close enough to work, is a time-honored tradition here, isn't it? It reminds me a little of the call-and-response aspects of some church services. I've participated many times.

I did pretty well on this one...well enough to expect most of the comments to be complaints about lowered bars, but didn't see a lot of that (yet). The only thing I looked up was "plural of genie," just to be sure.

@Terry
Paper and pen, buddy.
Problem solved.

@Lewis
Rye bread is wonderful, but the thought of peanut butter with it (much less jam) is just awful, IMHO.  Neither-- or None-- will be iimproved by the combination!
Is nothing sacred?

@Chris

That was my experience, too.  PBJS felt like a guess, but really, what alternatives are there?  (Not many kids get BLTS in their lunch box!)
With the J in, JEWISH RYE felt like a gimme, and the NW fell quite quickly.

@Times Rita
That's not a Natick. A Natick requires the crossing of two proper nouns. ALIA is a common noun, at least in this context.

A Natick also requires the proper nouns to be obscure, and Dennis LEHANE is a well-known and bestselling author. I have one of his novels (Shutter Island) on my coffee table waiting to be read.

@Norman

Let the goyim eat the RYE.

Remembering back to Sunday School days and the ways of the orthodox in cleaning all "chametz" from the house, I'm guessing that (orthodox) Jewish bakers must take a holiday during Pesach.

@Andrzej

I wrote this before I looked at other comments, and it looks like you're in the majority on this one.

As ever, mileage may vary.

@Katie
Being a big PBJ fan myself, I had that before I got to the bread problem.  When I typed in PBJS I thought to myself, what is going to start with J?

I got hooked on Reuben's living in Back  Bay  Boston 50 years ago.  Some deli near my office had great ones!

@Barry Ancona
"Named after me" is here a bit of wordplay. Perhaps not amusing to all. 
But if your presumption is that I do not recognize the difference between my name and words that are not my name, rest assured that that presumption is incorrect.

@Judy

He was amazing this is my favorite Oscar opening ever  (if you want you can jump to his musical medley at the end)

<a href="https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=UCAi1744Sa0" target="_blank">https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=UCAi1744Sa0</a>

@HeathieJ 
Absolutely! I really wasn't directing my comments at you. I was just generally commenting on what's common for some is uncommon for others and we should all keep that in mind when posting in the forum here.
Plus, wanted to support my fellow homies that didn't know the name of that author whose name I won't mention again ;)

@Renegator 
Well, the sitcom, soap opera, police procedural, variety show, and other common TV show types are all based on radio show formats. And radio shows took their inspiration from Vaudeville and other live art forms. So yeah, seems irrelevant now, but that's only if you like to ignore history.
Glad I could inspire a chuckle!

@Calhouri

If I tried to rate my senility level by my relative performance on these crosswords, I'd go insane before I ever got to senile.

XWStats says 32% of people who post there solved it slower than their average and 68% solved it faster. It rates this puzzle as an average Saturday (because they factor in the assumption that everyone is getting better and will tend to beat their own averages).

@Bandit

All I could first think is “prince doesn’t fit there.”

He only wanted to see us dancing in the purple rain.

@Renegator

I had "ill" as the fulfillment center for a moment. Whoops.

And I had such trouble ditching SPACESHip. I knew "lep" couldn't be right for 42A, but I held on to that ship for sooo long. Even tried to think of a variation of "golden rule" or "got engaged" to fix my "lep" problem... Didn't help that tennis and car models are not in my wheelhouse.

@Joe

It's a tennis thing, but that's all I know.

You made me laugh out loud, even though I disagree.
